{{short description|A volcanic seamount to the north of New Zealand in the Kermadec arc}} {{Infobox Seamount | Name = Monowai Seamount | Depth = {{Convert|132|m|ft|0}}<ref name="volcano">{{cite gvp|vn=242050 |name=Monowai |accessdate=2018-01-04}}</ref> | Map = | Summit area = | Location = North of the [[Kermadec Islands]]; south of [[Tonga]] | Group = | Coordinates = {{coord|25.887|S|177.188|W|}} | Country = New Zealand | Type = | Volcanic group = | Age = | Last eruption = August 2012 | Discovered = | Discovered by = | First visit = | Translation = | Language = | Pronunciation = | Photo = }} '''Monowai''' is a [[Volcano|volcanic]] [[seamount]] to the north of [[New Zealand]]. It is one of the most active volcanoes in the [[Kermadec Islands|Kermadec volcanic arc]] and has erupted many times since 1977.<ref>[http://www.volcano.si.edu/world/volcano.cfm?vnum=0402-05-&volpage=erupt Global Volcanism Program: Monowai Seamount, eruptive history]</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Rise and fall of underwater volcano revealed |author=[[David Shukman]] |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-18040658 |newspaper=BBC News |date=13 May 2012 |accessdate=2012-05-13}}</ref> {{coord|25.887|S|177.188|W|display=title}}
==Description== The summit of Monowai is approximately {{Convert|132|m|ft|0}}<ref name="volcano" /> below sea level, considerably above the level of the nearby [[Tonga Trench|Tonga]] and [[Kermadec Trench]]es. The summit's position and depth changed between 1998 and 2004, due to a landslide and eruptive regrowth. A {{Convert|1500|m}} deep [[caldera]], {{Convert|13|by|8|km|abbr=on}}, lies {{convert|5|to(-)|15|km|mi|abbr=on}} NNE of the seamount's main cone.
Monowai was discovered by an aerial survey in 1944. Subsequent surveys showed evidence of significant change - sea discolouration and seismic activity. Studies between 1978 and 2007 showed the summit repeatedly rising and falling.<ref name="BBC 13 May 2012"/>
==2010s== Sonar data from the research ship ''R/V Sonne'' showed that between May 14 and June 1–2, 2011 the summit collapsed by as much as {{Convert|18.8|m|ft|abbr=on}} and lava flows had raised another area by {{Convert|79.1|m|ft|abbr=on}}. Additionally a new volcanic cone was created. The ''R/V Sonne'' also observed the sea to be a yellowy-green with gas bubbles. Researchers believe that only [[Vesuvius]] and [[Mount St Helens]] have recorded larger growth rates.<ref name="BBC 13 May 2012">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-18040658 BBC, News, Science - Environment, Rise and fall of underwater volcano revealed. by David Shukman]</ref>
In August 2012, a {{Convert|25000|km2|abbr=on}} [[2012 Kermadec Islands eruption and pumice raft|floating raft of pumice]] was found offshore from New Zealand. It was initially believed to be from Monowai,<ref>{{Cite web |author1=Field, Michael |author2=Kirk, Stacey |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/science/7455060/25-000-sq-km-sea-of-pumice-floats-off-New-Zealand |title=25,000 sq km sea of pumice floats off New Zealand |date=8 August 2012 |publisher=Stuff.co.nz |accessdate=2012-08-10}}</ref><ref name="BBC20120810">{{Cite news |title=Vast volcanic 'raft' found in Pacific, near New Zealand |date=10 August 2012 |publisher=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-19207810 |accessdate=2012-08-10}}</ref> but Monowai was later ruled out as a possible source.<ref name=Stuff.co.nz>{{cite news| last =Cooke| first =Michelle| title =Scientists rock theory on pumice raft| newspaper =Stuff.co.nz| location =| pages = | publisher =| date =11 August 2012| url =http://www.stuff.co.nz/science/7461485/Scientists-rock-theory-on-pumice-raft| accessdate =13 August 2012 }}</ref>
